@lautenbach_adopted
on-arrival: lautenbach_plan_active = 1; bruning_austerity_accepted = 0; economic_plan = 5; budget -= 3; unemployed -= 3.5; economic_growth += 0.18; z_relation += 5; dvp_relation += 3; reformist_strength += 5; center_strength += 5; left_dissent += 5; workers_spd += 4*(1-dissent); new_middle_spd += 4*(1-dissent); old_middle_spd += 3*(1-dissent); pro_republic += 3; fiscal_stance -= 0.10; demand_impulse += 0.15; supply_impulse += 0.12; price_pressure += 0.05;

After intensive negotiations, a miracle occurs—the coalition approves a modified Lautenbach Plan!

[? if unemployed >= 25 : The catastrophic unemployment crisis convinced even conservatives that desperate times require bold measures. ?]

[? if schacht_relation >= 25 : Hjalmar Schacht's endorsement proved decisive. His support gave the plan establishment credibility that no socialist proposal could achieve. ?]

The Reichsbank will extend 1.5 billion marks in credit (reduced from Lautenbach's proposed 2 billion). Major infrastructure projects will proceed. Monetary policy relaxes. Gold standard restrictions ease.

It's not the full program—conservatives forced compromises—but it represents a fundamental shift from deflation to reflation. Government spending increases. Credit flows. Employment begins rising.

The technocratic framing proved crucial. By avoiding "socialist" rhetoric and emphasizing productive investment, Lautenbach made intervention palatable to center-right parties. The DVP accepts what they would never accept from trade unions.

Our reformist and center factions are pleased—this is pragmatic economic management that works. The left wing grumbles that it's "too timid" and "capitalist," but even they acknowledge it's better than Brüning's austerity.

Most importantly, the economy responds. Unemployment declines. The deflationary spiral slows. Germany demonstrates that there are alternatives to austerity.

Brüning's austerity program is shelved.

- @root: Continue.

@lautenbach_rejected
on-arrival: lautenbach_plan_rejected = 1; bruning_austerity_accepted = 1; budget += 2.5; unemployed += 5; economic_growth -= 0.65; workers_spd -= 7; unemployed_spd -= 8; workers_kpd += 4; unemployed_kpd += 7; workers_nsdap += 3; unemployed_nsdap += 4; left_dissent += 15; labor_dissent += 12; z_relation -= 3; dvp_relation -= 3; reformist_dissent += 8; coalition_dissent += 2; inflation -= 0.4; fiscal_stance += 0.18; demand_impulse -= 0.22; price_pressure -= 0.12; distribution_shift -= 0.06;

Despite our advocacy, the coalition rejects the Lautenbach Plan. The Center Party's fiscal conservatives prevail. The DVP fears "monetary experimentation." Chancellor Brüning dismisses it as inflationary fantasy.

"Germany cannot afford financial adventures," they declare.

Instead, a compromise austerity program proceeds—not as severe as Brüning's original proposal, but still deflationary. Spending cuts. Wage reductions. Tax increases. The crisis deepens.

Our reformists are frustrated—we had a workable alternative and the coalition refused it. The party advocated for economic sense and was ignored.

The working class suffers. Unemployment continues rising. Support bleeds to KPD and NSDAP. The deflationary death spiral continues.

[? if unemployed >= 25 : Historians will note that Germany had the Lautenbach Plan available in 1931—a technically sound alternative to austerity during a catastrophic crisis—and chose not to implement it. ?]

- @root: Continue.

@leave_coalition
choose-if: spd_toleration = 0
unavailable-subtitle: [? if spd_toleration = 1 : We are already only tolerating the government. ?]
on-arrival: spd_in_government = 0; in_grand_coalition = 0; in_weimar_coalition = 0; spd_toleration = 1; chancellor = "Brüning"; chancellor_party = "Z"; bruning_austerity_accepted = 1; lautenbach_plan_rejected = 1; left_dissent -= 10; labor_dissent -= 8; reformist_dissent += 5; center_dissent += 8; pro_republic -= 3;

We leave the government. "We will not implement policies that starve workers, nor will we remain while the coalition rejects sensible alternatives," we announce.

Brüning forms a new government without us, governing through Article 48 emergency decrees with Hindenburg's support. The austerity program proceeds anyway—and the Lautenbach Plan is forgotten entirely.

The consequences are mixed:

Our working-class credibility is preserved—we opposed the cuts, at least. The left wing is satisfied. Labor unions appreciate our stand.

But we've lost all influence over economic policy. Brüning implements even harsher measures without SPD moderation. And we've stepped away from defending the Republic when it needed us most.

[? if pro_republic < 40 : The Republic's defenders grow fewer. Who will protect democracy now? ?]

- @root: Continue.
